posts.name: joel truher
posts.cooked:
Hi everybody (especially @Oblarg ),

We’re planning to overhaul our logging this fall, with the goal of supporting USB logging through DataLogManager, and live logging through Glass, for all the quantities we need to see.  There are no other goals – we don’t use Shuffleboard or SmartDashboard or whatever, and for us NT is just one-way, write-only.

In the past, we’ve used Sendables, and we’ve started to just use NetworkTables directly, but it’s quite verbose.  I’ve been looking at the Oblog annotations, and I’m curious if that would give us what we need?  Does Oblog work with DataLogManager?

Thanks!

posts.cooked: you should take a look at 6328 AdvantageKit

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: AdvantageKit does a lot more than just logging.  If you have no other goals than just logging data, the SmartDashboard interfaces are pretty straightforward (and everything put to NT gets logged).  Unfortunately, I’m not sure Oblog is still being maintained; @Oblarg ?

posts.name: joel truher
posts.cooked: re smartdashboard, yeah, my annoyance with it is that I’d like to minimize magic.  you put a key and a value in one end, you get them out the other.  I like the NT4 direct route for that reason, it’s just so wordy.

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: Yeah the NT API is verbose mainly because of all the functionality it needs to expose.  There’s a clear tension between minimizing magic and being verbose, it sounds like you want something in between the two.  There’s a proposal for an higher-level Telemetry API that would supersede SmartDashboard that might match what you’re looking for, but the first attempt at an implementation stalled out because it seemed like it essentially evolved into a reimplementation of what already exists in Sendable.

posts.name: Amicus1
posts.cooked: Oblog does not work with DataLogManager. If you’re looking at 2024, I’m developing a “spiritual successor” to Oblog that has integration with DataLog and NT4.

posts.name: Chris Gerth
posts.cooked:
For “Yet Another NT4 Based Logging Solution”, python edition:

Critically, we wanted to wrapper NT4 and logging such that:

A trivial interface for indicating what needed to be logged - restricting to scalar doubles and Booleans was acceptable.

Automatically dump “thing to be logged” into NT4 where every tool for debugging could see it, plus put it to disk so we could extract log files after the match

Do not naively log everything in NT, since we’ve been known to abuse it in the past

Samples from the same loop should have aligned timestamps

While we’d rather have java annotations, we settled for

log("name of thing", val_of_thing)

posts.name: joel truher
posts.cooked:
ok, sounds like we should make our own thing, which is fine.

while i have the log-interested folk’s attention, is there some simple trick to get the Driver Station Log fields (e.g. battery voltage, CAN utilization, rio CPU, etc) into the DataLogManager USB output?

posts.name: Joe Ross
posts.cooked: Battery Voltage and CAN Utilization are exposed in the RobotController class along with potentially other useful things. See getBatteryVoltage() and getCANStatus()

posts.name: joel truher
posts.cooked: Yes, thank you.  What I’m aiming for is a one-liner that stuffs those useful things into the network-tables-based DataLogManager output file, so I don’t have to join the two separate log files later.

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: We don’t currently have a one-liner for RobotController like we do for DriverStation.  PRs accepted!

posts.name: Eli Barnett
posts.cooked:
Oblog works over NT, and so works with WPILib data logs implicitly if you (as described above) turn on logging of NT values.  It is not as performant as calling the DataLogManager functions directly, but it shouldn’t matter unless you’re logging a lot of things, or using some of the more deeply-reflective fanciness like the methodName feature.

I’d very much like to sunset Oblog in favor of a modern tool that integrates directly with the more-performant WPILog features, but I don’t have time to rewrite the tool from scratch and it doesn’t make sense to do absent some of the other telemetry reworks. Sendable is ancient and troublesome.

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: Nice, I like the external API shape.  My only concern with that code is that the lambda in the log() functions will probably create a new object on every call.  Potentially escape analysis will catch it and make it so it doesn’t hit the full GC, but I’m not sure if the JVM is that smart.  Just something to be aware of if you make lots of log() calls.

posts.name: Sam Carlberg
posts.cooked: The lambdas functions are small and simple enough that the JIT will inline them to direct method calls. It’ll take a few thousand invocations until the JVM determines that it’s an optimization target, though, so storing the functions in constants would avoid any object allocations until the JIT kicks in
